                    <note>
                        <ab type="history">A variant of the term Tǝgrāy first appears in a <date
                                notBefore="0900" notAfter="0999">10th-century</date> gloss to
                                <persName ref="PRS3204CosmasI">Cosmas Indicopleustes</persName>,
                            although its origin and meaning are unclear. Historical Tǝgrāy was the
                            most important northern province of <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop"
                                >Ethiopia</placeName> due to its symbolic, economic and strategic
                            power. It encompassed <placeName ref="LOC1264Adwa">ʿAdwā</placeName>,
                                <placeName ref="LOC1310Aksum">ʾAksum</placeName> and <placeName
                                ref="LOC6384Yeha">Yǝḥa</placeName>, but it also extended and
                            controlled adiacent territories, periodically including other areas
                            beyond its central core. Territories that were often and for long
                            periods of time subject to Tǝgrāy's control include <placeName
                                ref="LOC3826Hawzen">Ḥāwzen</placeName> and <placeName
                                ref="LOC2973Enticc">Ǝnṭiḉḉo</placeName> and sometimes also
                                <placeName ref="LOC5749Sire">Šire</placeName> and <placeName
                                ref="LOC5882Tamben">Tamben</placeName>. Tǝgrāy was densely populated
                            since ancient times and characterised by the interaction between Semitic
                            and Cushitic groups with southern Arabian influences. The capital of
                            historical Tǝgrāy changed over time. Tǝgrāy owed part of its importantce
                            to the sacred town of <placeName ref="LOC1310Aksum">ʾAksum</placeName>
                            that was part of its territory, althugh enjoyed its own self-government.
                        </ab>
                    </note>
